






Energy Density of Vortices in the Schrodinger Picture 

FSU TPI 02/03 

J.D. Lange[1], M. Engelhardt[2]
and H. Reinhardt[2] 




[1] Theoretisch-Physikalisches Institut,
Friedrich-Schiller-Universitat Jena, Frobelstieg 1, 07743 Jena,
Germany [1]J.D.Laenge@tpi.uni-jena.de  

[2] Institut fur Theoretische Physik,
Eberhard-Karls-Universitat Tubingen, Auf der Morgenstelle 14, 72076
Tubingen, Germany [2]engelm@tphys.physik.uni-tuebingen.de,
hugo.reinhardt@uni-tuebingen.de   



 
The one-loop
energy density of an infinitely thin static magnetic vortex in 
Yang-Mills theory is evaluated using the Schrodinger picture. Both the
gluonic fluctuations as well as the quarks in the vortex background are
included. The
energy density of the magnetic vortex is discussed as
a function of the magnetic flux. The center vortices correspond to local minima
in the effective potential. These minima are degenerated with the perturbative
vacuum if the fermions are ignored. Inclusion of fermions lifts this
degeneracy, raising the vortex energy above the energy of the perturbative
vacuum.

02.30.Sa, 02.30.Tb, 03.70.+k, 11.15.-q 

center vortices, self-adjoint extensions, one-loop energy 

Introduction 

Recently, there has been a revival of the vortex picture of confinement
. Lattice calculations performed in the so-called maximal center
gauge with subsequent center projection (which provides a simple
method for identifying the center vortices in Yang-Mills configurations) have
given substantial support to the idea that center vortices are the relevant
infrared degrees of freedom responsible for confinement. The deconfinement
phase transition in the vortex picture takes the guise of a percolation
transition. Furthermore, the topological charge of the vortices
can be understood in terms of their self-intersection number
 and the spontaneous breaking of chiral symmetry
can be generated through vortex effects.

On the other hand, while a successful phenomenological model of vortex
dynamics has been developed, 
investigations of the dynamical properties of Yang-Mills vortices have
only recently been launched, cf. for thick center
vortices and for thin vortices of arbitrary flux. In the present
paper, we expand on these investigations, which only considered gluonic
fluctuations to one-loop order, by evaluating the one-loop energy density
of an infinitely thin static magnetic vortex including quark fluctuations.
For this purpose we use the Schrodinger picture.  We
solve the Schrodinger equation for gluonic fluctuations and fermions
moving in the vortex background field.
From  the obtained eigenenergies we calculate the
static energy density of the vortex as a function of its magnetic flux.
We will show that the
inclusion of fermions substantially changes the energy density of the vortex.
In particular we will find that the fermions raise the
center vortex effective energy compared with the perturbative vacuum.

The organization of the paper is as follows: In the next section we study the
Schrodinger equation for the gluonic fluctuations around the vortex
background field.
In subsection  we study the Hamiltonian of the gluonic
fluctuations in the vortex background and discuss its self-adjoint extensions
in subsection . Subsection  is devoted to the
incorporation of Gauss' law and to the selection of the appropriate
self-adjoint extension of the Hamiltonian of the gluonic fluctuations.
In subsection  the
gluonic contribution to the energy density of the vortex is presented.

In section  we study fermions in the vortex background field and
calculate their contribution to the energy density. The physical
interpretation of our results and some concluding remarks are given in
section .

