Gauss' law and choice of self-adjoint extension 

In the previous section, for the cases 
 a whole family of self-adjoint
extensions of the operator  was obtained, labeled by one
continuous parameter ; each value corresponds to a different
choice of boundary conditions reflecting different
physical situations. In this section, a definite choice for the
parameter  will be motivated.

The operator , cf. (), can be interpreted physically
as the Hamiltonian of a particle with effective angular momentum (grand spin)
 in a potential 
. Therefore,
a bound state can only arise if the potential term is negative,
i.e.  for positive flux . 
This is the case for
 and for .
It will now be demonstrated that Gauss' law forbids bound states even in
these two cases.

In order to fulfill Gauss' law, it is necessary to restrict the
set of functions  in each subspace of definite eigenvalue
 to those linear combinations which satisfy eq. ().
Since the corresponding operator  does not mix
functions  with a different color quantum number , such
linear combinations can be constructed for each  separately.
The same is true for the momentum in 3-direction  and the angular
momentum quantum number . Concentrating on the bound state
solutions in the case , one has, using
the decomposition (),
 
which for the bound state solutions 
